explanation:
Reason each symbol is required to decide if code in OS_ConsoleTask_Entry is dead (i.e. removal would not affect program behaviour):

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Determines whether the initial if-body ever executes. If this always fails (or always succeeds) the body/loop behaviour changes; its success conditions and side-effects are essential for dead-code analysis.

- OS_VoidPtrValueWrapper_t: The union/struct layout (opaque_arg vs id) defines how the input arg maps to the id used by OS_ObjectIdGetById; this affects whether the call can succeed, so it must be known.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT: The lock mode passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById may change lookup semantics (refcounting, ownership) and thus affect whether the call succeeds or has side-effects that matter.

- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONSOLE: The object type argument influences the lookup target; required to know if a console object can be found for the given id.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type and its semantics (valid range, lifetime, how it represents an object) are needed to reason about the valid use of the token, whether OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET yields a valid local, and whether the token must be released.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/function that maps token -> object pointer. Required to know whether 'local' can be NULL/invalid and whether retrieving local has side-effects (e.g. reference count modifications) relevant to dead-code judgment.

- OS_impl_console_table: The object table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; needed to determine whether the token indexes a real entry and to inspect table contents/validity.

- OS_impl_console_internal_record_t: Definition of the 'local' record (notably the type of data_sem and any other fields used). Needed to confirm local->data_sem exists and to reason about interactions with other code (who posts it).

- sem_wait: The blocking semantics of sem_wait determine whether the loop body can block indefinitely or return; whether removing the sem_wait (or the whole loop) would change observables depends on its behavior.

- sem_post: Needed to know which other code can wake this task (post the semaphore). If no code posts the semaphore then sem_wait always blocks and behavior differs; identifying poster(s) is required to decide dead-ness.

- sem_t: The semaphore type and lifetime semantics (initialized/uninitialized) help determine whether sem_wait is valid and whether removing semaphore operations affects program behaviour.

- OS_ConsoleOutput_Impl: Called inside the loop; must know its observable side-effects (I/O, blocking, state changes) to judge whether removing the call would change program behaviour.

- OS_ConsoleWakeup_Impl: A likely producer of the semaphore wake for console tasks (and shown in static call graph). Knowing whether this or similar functions post the console data_sem is necessary to establish whether the loop body ever runs after initial entry.

- OS_SharedGlobalVars: The GlobalState field is tested in the while loop; need its declaration and who/where it is modified to determine whether the loop terminates and whether removal of the loop body affects shutdown behaviour.

- OS_SHUTDOWN_MAGIC_NUMBER: The sentinel value compared against GlobalState; required to reason whether the while loop condition can change (and thus whether the loop is meaningful or removable).

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token on exit; its side-effects (resource cleanup, refcount change) are relevant to behavior. Removing the call could change system state even if the loop is unreachable, so its semantics must be known.

In short: to decide whether any operation in OS_ConsoleTask_Entry is dead, one must know (1) if the initial object lookup ever succeeds, (2) whether the loop body executes or is permanently blocked, (3) which other code can wake the task and thus make the loop meaningful, (4) whether ConsoleOutput has observable effects, and (5) whether token release affects global state. The symbols above provide the necessary definitions/behaviour to answer those questions.
